def to_millions(df: pd.DataFrame) -> pd.DataFrame:
    # copy
    df = df.copy()

    # get cols that are not the zone
    cols_not_zone = [col for col in df.columns if col != 'ZONA']

    # each row to millions
    df[cols_not_zone] = df[cols_not_zone].apply(lambda x: x/1e6)
    return df

Time series decomposition: trend, seasonality and residuals¶

# decompose time series to see trend, seasonality and residuals
from statsmodels.tsa.seasonal import seasonal_decompose

def decompose_ts(s: pd.Series, period=12) -> None:
    # decompose
    decomposition = seasonal_decompose(s, model='additive', period=period)

    # plot
    decomposition.plot()

    ax.plot(theta, year_data['total_sales'], color=color_palette[i])

In [27]:
# plot time series of sales
def plot_time_series(df, maxy):
    # copy
    df = df.copy()
    # set index
    df.set_index('ZONA', inplace=True)

    # plot time series using seaborn, lines should be solid
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(10, 5))
    sns.lineplot(data=df.T, dashes=False)
    # set title
    zones = df.index.unique()
    zones = [str(zone) for zone in zones]
    ax.set_title('Time Series of Sales. \nZones: ' + ', '.join(zones))
    # show legend
    ax.legend()
    # x ticks should be dates and only show the semester
    ax.set_xticks(df.columns[::6])
    ax.set_xticklabels(df.columns[::6], rotation=45)
    # set x label
    ax.set_xlabel('Date')
    # set y limits
    ax.set_ylim(0, maxy)

    # show plot
    plt.show()
    return None
